===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|brouken||to use, enjoy|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|brūcan||to enjoy, brook, use, possess, partake of, spend}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*brūkaną||to enjoy, use}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*bʰrūg-||to enjoy}}. Cognate with {{etyl|sco|-}} {{term|brook|lang=sco}}, {{term|brouk||to use, enjoy|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|brûke||to use|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|bruiken||to use|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|brauchen||to need, require, use|lang=de}}, {{etyl|no|-}} {{term|bruke||to use|lang=no}}, {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|fruor||enjoy|lang=la}}. Related to {{l/en|fruit}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|transitive|obsolete|except in Scots|lang=en}} To [[use]]; [[enjoy]]; have the full employment of.
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[earn]]; [[deserve]].
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[bear]]; [[endure]]; [[support]]; [[put up with]]; [[tolerate]] (''usually used in the negative, with an [[abstract noun]] as object'').
#: ''I will not '''brook''' any disobedience.''
#: ''I will '''brook''' no refusal.''
